00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:19.070 --> 00:00:20.790
&gt;&gt; Betsy Peterson:
Well, hello everyone.

00:00:20.790 --> 00:00:24.550 position:56%
I am Betsy Peterson, the Director
of the American Folklife Center here

00:00:24.550 --> 00:00:28.770
at the Library of Congress, and
on behalf of all of the staff,

00:00:28.770 --> 00:00:32.630
I want to welcome you here today.

00:00:32.630 --> 00:00:37.950
We are at a Botkin Lecture that is
part of the Botkin Lecture series,

00:00:37.950 --> 00:00:42.580 position:56%
and the Botkin Lecture Series allows
the American Folklife Center to work

00:00:42.580 --> 00:00:46.680
with leading scholars, artists,
activists and others involved

00:00:46.680 --> 00:00:51.190
in the disciplines of folklore,
folk music, ethomusicology,

00:00:51.190 --> 00:00:53.550
oral history and cultural heritage.

00:00:53.550 --> 00:00:57.670
It also allows us to
enhance our archives as well.

00:00:57.670 --> 00:01:04.180
In 2014, the AFC began to widen
the scope of the Botkin Lectures

00:01:04.180 --> 00:01:07.320
to include open mic
sessions like the one

00:01:07.320 --> 00:01:09.610
that we're going to
have this afternoon.

00:01:09.610 --> 00:01:13.410
And during the open mic sessions,
we invite the public in to listen

00:01:13.410 --> 00:01:16.090
to an actual archival interview,

00:01:16.090 --> 00:01:23.620
and the center very proudly traces
this type of activity back to 1938

00:01:23.620 --> 00:01:28.550 position:56%
when Allen Lomax, who was also an
employee of the archive at the time,

00:01:28.550 --> 00:01:32.450
sat on the stage of the Coolidge
Auditorium right next door

00:01:32.450 --> 00:01:36.340
and recorded an interview with
the legendary jazz musician,

00:01:36.340 --> 00:01:37.830
Jelly Roll Morton.

00:01:37.830 --> 00:01:39.640
For the center and the library,

00:01:39.640 --> 00:01:42.680
the Botkin Lecture Series
is also an important part

00:01:42.680 --> 00:01:45.950 position:56%
of our acquisitions activities here.

00:01:45.950 --> 00:01:50.310
Each lecture is videotaped and
documented and becomes part

00:01:50.310 --> 00:01:52.230
of our permanent collections.

00:01:52.230 --> 00:01:56.710
In addition, Botkin events
are later posted as webcasts

00:01:56.710 --> 00:02:00.190
on the library's webcast so
that we can share it with people

00:02:00.190 --> 00:02:02.970
around the world and
so that it is available

00:02:02.970 --> 00:02:05.390
for future generations as well.

00:02:05.390 --> 00:02:06.930
So with all of that said,

00:02:06.930 --> 00:02:11.860
please turn off any cell
phones at this point.

00:02:11.860 --> 00:02:14.020
We would appreciate it.

00:02:14.020 --> 00:02:19.010
And now, today -- today is a
very exciting open mic session.

00:02:19.010 --> 00:02:23.790
I have the honor of introducing
Mark Moss whose been the editor,

00:02:23.790 --> 00:02:30.700 position:56%
executive director and guiding light
of [inaudible] magazine since 1983.

00:02:30.700 --> 00:02:34.370
When people talk about the North
American folk music revival,

00:02:34.370 --> 00:02:37.630
the first thing that comes to
mind, of course, are the artists,

00:02:37.630 --> 00:02:41.300
musicians, performers, revivalists,

00:02:41.300 --> 00:02:46.500
singer songwriters whose artistry
has filled stages, coffee houses,

00:02:46.500 --> 00:02:51.510
festivals, vinyl grooves since
the 1950's, but in addition

00:02:51.510 --> 00:02:57.520
to the performers or in conjunction
with the performers I should say,

00:02:57.520 --> 00:03:02.430
the folk music revival also gave
rise to a complex support network

00:03:02.430 --> 00:03:07.300
that included concert and record
producers, venue and club owners,

00:03:07.300 --> 00:03:11.710
nonprofits, record labels,
radio stations and announcers,

00:03:11.710 --> 00:03:17.930
festival programs, programmers
and on and on and on.

00:03:17.930 --> 00:03:22.230
In fact, the folk music
revival was significantly aided,

00:03:22.230 --> 00:03:26.660
shaped and documented by this
network and by a whole range

00:03:26.660 --> 00:03:31.020
of folk music newsletters,
journals and magazines.

00:03:31.020 --> 00:03:35.830
And of course, of all of these,
I think none was more important,

00:03:35.830 --> 00:03:39.430
innovative or influential
as Sing Out Magazine.

00:03:39.430 --> 00:03:41.580
Today, Sing Out editor, Mark Moss,

00:03:41.580 --> 00:03:45.500
will be discussing the
legendary publication

00:03:45.500 --> 00:03:50.620 position:56%
and the seminole role it played in
the American folk song music revival

00:03:50.620 --> 00:03:54.860
and also just talk about the
significance and challenges

00:03:54.860 --> 00:03:57.880
of folk music journalism today.

00:03:57.880 --> 00:04:03.480
To do this, he will be joined
by two AFC staff members,

00:04:03.480 --> 00:04:05.590
Nancy Groce and Steve Winick.

00:04:05.590 --> 00:04:09.480
So at this point, welcome
Mark, and I'm going to turn

00:04:09.480 --> 00:04:12.070
over everything to Nancy and Steve.

00:04:12.070 --> 00:04:13.370
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Welcome.

00:04:13.370 --> 00:04:16.990
Thank you all so much for coming,
especially to Mark for coming

00:04:16.990 --> 00:04:20.360
down from Pennsylvania
to Washington.

00:04:20.360 --> 00:04:25.650
Okay, so what I thought we'd do is
talk to you a bit about the history

00:04:25.650 --> 00:04:28.180
of Sing Out in particular.

00:04:28.180 --> 00:04:29.480
We have some pictures.

00:04:29.480 --> 00:04:33.620
Maybe we'll wait until the
middle to show some images

00:04:33.620 --> 00:04:37.730
and then talk more broadly
about the role of journalism

00:04:37.730 --> 00:04:42.370
in traditional music and folk
music in the United Staes.

00:04:42.370 --> 00:04:43.670
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Okay.

00:04:43.670 --> 00:04:44.970
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Sounds good?

00:04:44.970 --> 00:04:46.270
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Sure.

00:04:46.270 --> 00:04:47.570
But for those familiar with the
Jelly Roll Morton interviews

00:04:47.570 --> 00:04:50.330
that Betsy talked about, we will
try not to go on for nuine hours,

00:04:50.330 --> 00:04:55.450
but if we do, I see a grammy
