00:04:55.450 --> 00:04:58.620
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: I know my
Mom would be [inaudible].

00:04:58.620 --> 00:05:01.680
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: So tell us
a little bit about yourself.

00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:05.110
How did you come to
be editor of Sing Out?

00:05:05.110 --> 00:05:11.010
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: Well, in 1972, well
into the history of Sing Out,

00:05:11.010 --> 00:05:16.040
I went to Philadelphia folk
festival, and there was a booth

00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:20.520
in the back of the festival that
was set up with decades worth

00:05:20.520 --> 00:05:24.210
of back issues of the magazine,
and I kind of sauntered up there,

00:05:24.210 --> 00:05:27.610
met a fellow by the
name of Josh Dodson

00:05:27.610 --> 00:05:32.500
who was running a group
called [inaudible].

00:05:32.500 --> 00:05:35.620
Met a fellow named Josh Dodson

00:05:35.620 --> 00:05:37.970
who was running an organization
called Friends of Sing

00:05:37.970 --> 00:05:39.270
Out at the time, which is kind

00:05:39.270 --> 00:05:45.190
of a fundraising booster support
organization, and I just said --

00:05:45.190 --> 00:05:50.880
I was 14 years old and
said, "Hey, can I help?"

00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:59.290 position:56%
So because to me as a -- somebody
who liked folk music who liked music

00:05:59.290 --> 00:06:03.670
in general and wanted to
find out where it came from,

00:06:03.670 --> 00:06:08.430
what traditions were, was really
getting into a lot of early music.

00:06:08.430 --> 00:06:12.940 position:56%
We'd gone to summer camp and been
brought up on the Weavers and Peter,

00:06:12.940 --> 00:06:22.430 position:56%
Paul and Mary, etc. This was really
-- I felt like I had found my thing.

00:06:22.430 --> 00:06:25.860
So I started at that point,
that was my first Sing Out booth

00:06:25.860 --> 00:06:31.860
and then throughout the 70's
when I went to college and then

00:06:31.860 --> 00:06:38.220
after college ever summer I would
do half dozen or more festivals.

00:06:38.220 --> 00:06:41.950
I would load up a car with
all packages of Sing Out,

00:06:41.950 --> 00:06:45.420
take them to festivals, sell
subscriptions and things like that.

00:06:45.420 --> 00:06:46.720
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: [Inaudible]
volunteer?

00:06:46.720 --> 00:06:48.940
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: It was
strictly as a volunteer.

00:06:48.940 --> 00:06:51.490
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: So you mentioned
the Philadelphia Folk Festival.

00:06:51.490 --> 00:06:56.520
Was that a big part of your sort
of induction into folk music

00:06:56.520 --> 00:07:00.970
or you were starting to
be involved in the scene?

00:07:00.970 --> 00:07:08.280
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: Well, I saw Arlo
Guthrie at Carnegie Hall in 1970

00:07:08.280 --> 00:07:11.060
and I mean, I was already
into the music,

00:07:11.060 --> 00:07:16.990
but it was the first
festival that I'd gone to.

00:07:16.990 --> 00:07:24.260
And I -- so -- but I already
had a growing interest

00:07:24.260 --> 00:07:33.700
in traditional music and blues,
old time music, [inaudible] music

00:07:33.700 --> 00:07:41.250
and was sort of looking beyond
the pop folk of the 1960's era

00:07:41.250 --> 00:07:46.070
into the more rooted oriented
stuff, and that's what was sort

00:07:46.070 --> 00:07:49.140
of surprising to me that there was
something like Sing Out out there.

00:07:49.140 --> 00:07:52.300
And honestly a kid growing
up in [inaudible] Valley

00:07:52.300 --> 00:07:55.600
in Pennsylvania hadn't really
come across it too much.

00:07:55.600 --> 00:08:01.030
I mean, so I became really
quickly and avidly involved

00:08:01.030 --> 00:08:02.580
in the magazine at that point.

00:08:02.580 --> 00:08:07.350
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: And the
magazine itself, just to go back

00:08:07.350 --> 00:08:09.470
to the history, was founded when?

00:08:09.470 --> 00:08:12.740
Do you want to talk a little
bit about the roots of Sing Out?

00:08:12.740 --> 00:08:17.240
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: At the end of the
second world war, there was a group

00:08:17.240 --> 00:08:24.890
of people including notably
Pete Seger, Woody Guthrie,

00:08:24.890 --> 00:08:31.050
Allen was involved in those days --

00:08:31.050 --> 00:08:33.080
[ Inaudible ]

00:08:33.080 --> 00:08:37.950
Paul Rosen was out of the country,
but he was sort of a revered --

00:08:37.950 --> 00:08:42.980
I mean, just to back track a
little bit, when these guys

00:08:42.980 --> 00:08:47.220
who had been part of the New
York City labor music scene

00:08:47.220 --> 00:08:52.470 position:56%
in the late 30's, early 40's had all
gone off into the second world war

00:08:52.470 --> 00:08:56.110
and when they came back, they
sort of got back together again

00:08:56.110 --> 00:09:00.030
and created an organization called
Peoples Artist, Incorporated,

00:09:00.030 --> 00:09:09.530 position:56%
which was really sort of a glorified
booking agency, union of artists

00:09:09.530 --> 00:09:15.460
who were often affiliated with
the Communist party in the U.S.

00:09:15.460 --> 00:09:20.370
and also very involved
with the labor movement.

00:09:20.370 --> 00:09:25.640
And they were -- they were acting
as a booking agency for each other

00:09:25.640 --> 00:09:32.230
to get both -- to work
collaboratively to do recordings

00:09:32.230 --> 00:09:38.450
and to get bookings at labor
meetings, strikes, demonstrations

00:09:38.450 --> 00:09:40.250
and things like that,
and they created

00:09:40.250 --> 00:09:45.290
in 1946 a newsletter
called People Songs.

00:09:45.290 --> 00:09:46.930
First issue was mimiographed

00:09:46.930 --> 00:09:51.220
in Oscar Brand's basement
on a mimiograph machine.

00:09:51.220 --> 00:09:56.130
But Oscar used to love
to tell that story.

00:09:56.130 --> 00:10:03.930
But -- and it went from -- and
Peoples Artist, while it began

00:10:03.930 --> 00:10:10.460
as a relatively small group
of musicians in New York City,

00:10:10.460 --> 00:10:15.880
developed satellite offices so
that there were offices in Arizona,

00:10:15.880 --> 00:10:23.690 position:56%
San Francisco, Chicago that were
all sharing this national newsletter

00:10:23.690 --> 00:10:24.990
that was --

00:10:24.990 --> 00:10:26.290
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: The Peoples Songs?

00:10:26.290 --> 00:10:28.860 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: The Peoples Songs that
was printing songs in the magazine

00:10:28.860 --> 00:10:34.340
as well as news and information
about networking and highlighting

00:10:34.340 --> 00:10:42.600
and trying to preserve and share,
classic labor songs and material,

00:10:42.600 --> 00:10:45.120
which was really integral to what
they were doing at that point.

00:10:45.120 --> 00:10:52.410
In 1948, they got very involved in
the Wallace campaign for president.

00:10:52.410 --> 00:10:56.530
And sort of overextended themselves

00:10:56.530 --> 00:11:02.720
so after the Wallace campaign was
unsuccessful as history knows,

00:11:02.720 --> 00:11:07.880
people saw and found themselves
really strapped for cash

00:11:07.880 --> 00:11:10.010
and decided to cancel the magazine.

00:11:10.010 --> 00:11:12.110
So they published one final issue,

00:11:12.110 --> 00:11:16.330
which was the first
issue of the fourth year.

00:11:16.330 --> 00:11:21.860
Each issue was -- the early
ones were just like four pages,

00:11:21.860 --> 00:11:23.990
but they got up to
being like 16 pages.

00:11:23.990 --> 00:11:25.290
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: So
fairly substantial.

00:11:25.290 --> 00:11:28.210
They had a couple thousand
subscribers at that point?

00:11:28.210 --> 00:11:32.440
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: I think that they
had like about 1200 subscribers

00:11:32.440 --> 00:11:36.830
at its largest distribution
at that point.

00:11:36.830 --> 00:11:41.700
And so the final issue was
just a list of names of people

00:11:41.700 --> 00:11:44.970
who had been involved
and contributed money

00:11:44.970 --> 00:11:49.740
and had been long time subscribers
saying that they were belly up

00:11:49.740 --> 00:11:53.150
and they were giving
up and that was it.

00:11:53.150 --> 00:11:57.110
And there was an outcry from
the membership saying hey,

00:11:57.110 --> 00:11:58.410
wait a minute.

00:11:58.410 --> 00:12:00.740
You didn't ask us what you wanted
us to do and if you wanted us

00:12:00.740 --> 00:12:04.640
to help the magazine
continue in some way.

00:12:04.640 --> 00:12:11.530
And out of those ashes in about
a year later in May of 1950,

00:12:11.530 --> 00:12:14.190
the first issue of
Sing Out was formed.

00:12:14.190 --> 00:12:19.440
Also, run -- the publishing
entity, the ownership of Sing

00:12:19.440 --> 00:12:23.390
Out was Peoples Arts, Incorporated
for the first eight years.

00:12:23.390 --> 00:12:29.800
Now, this was like the first
of many near bankruptcies

00:12:29.800 --> 00:12:32.240
that this group of people had.

00:12:32.240 --> 00:12:42.760
So in the 1950's, it quickly
developed from like a 16 page 5.5

00:12:42.760 --> 00:12:46.600
by 8.5 little pamphlet
that they had put

00:12:46.600 --> 00:12:56.410
out into a pretty substantial
64 then 128 then 164 page little

00:12:56.410 --> 00:13:02.330
magazine, but the 1950's were
like a touch time to be rooted

00:13:02.330 --> 00:13:03.900
in the communist party
and the labor movement.

00:13:03.900 --> 00:13:06.020
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Yeah, talk
about the political situation then

00:13:06.020 --> 00:13:12.190
because Peoples Songs come up in
all of the congressional testimony

00:13:12.190 --> 00:13:13.880
of people like Pete Seger
and all those folks.

00:13:13.880 --> 00:13:15.180
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: Right.

00:13:15.180 --> 00:13:17.050
Well, I mean, the interesting
this is, of course,

00:13:17.050 --> 00:13:19.580
because I was born in 1955.

00:13:19.580 --> 00:13:23.530
So I was a little young to
have first hand experiences,

00:13:23.530 --> 00:13:29.830
but I did have the honor and
benefit of being able to meet

00:13:29.830 --> 00:13:33.300
and spend some time with Irwin
Silber who was the editor of Sing

00:13:33.300 --> 00:13:43.830
Out after I think it's third
or fourth issue up until 1965.

00:13:43.830 --> 00:13:47.560 position:56%
From his perspective about it --
now, of course, this was years later

00:13:47.560 --> 00:13:51.760
and he was done with Sing Out
for many years after I met him.

00:13:51.760 --> 00:13:53.060
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: Right.

00:13:53.060 --> 00:13:55.410
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: But his perspective
of it was that it was strange

00:13:55.410 --> 00:13:58.950
that anybody thought that
Sing Out was somehow connected

00:13:58.950 --> 00:14:03.290
to the communist party because as
he put it, I never got a phone call

00:14:03.290 --> 00:14:06.640
from anybody at party
headquarters telling me what to do.

00:14:06.640 --> 00:14:10.270
We just did our thing.

00:14:10.270 --> 00:14:14.380
But realistically, I think
it would be irresponsible not

00:14:14.380 --> 00:14:20.580
to acknowledge the fact that these
were people that were at the heart

00:14:20.580 --> 00:14:27.610
and beginning of both the labor
movement from that period of time,

00:14:27.610 --> 00:14:32.190
certainly the beginnings of
the civil rights movement.

00:14:32.190 --> 00:14:38.170
Ultimately, women's rights,
anti-Vietnam, anti-war,

00:14:38.170 --> 00:14:43.490
all of that stuff was
central to what Sing

00:14:43.490 --> 00:14:46.600
Out was at that point in time.

00:14:46.600 --> 00:14:49.480
So they -- Irwin's
approach to this --

00:14:49.480 --> 00:14:55.640
because my later philosophy
about what I saw Sing Out as

00:14:55.640 --> 00:15:00.700
when I became the editor I had some
conversations with Irwin about it.

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:09.980
My feeling was always -- as a
lay person, as a nonpolitician,

00:15:09.980 --> 00:15:11.860
but somebody who loves history,

00:15:11.860 --> 00:15:16.310
I saw Sing Out as being a folk
music magazine that was influenced

00:15:16.310 --> 00:15:19.440
by the times and the
culture and the politics.

00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:21.650
Irwin did not see it that way.

00:15:21.650 --> 00:15:29.840
He saw it very much as trying
to create a political voice

00:15:29.840 --> 00:15:34.800
and doing it by using music
that he saw as a way to connect.

00:15:34.800 --> 00:15:43.040
So when he would do -- in the
very first issue of Sing Out,

00:15:43.040 --> 00:15:46.090
in fact back into the
Peoples Songs days,

00:15:46.090 --> 00:15:49.750
there was always what they called
international music section.

00:15:49.750 --> 00:15:53.470
Now this was decades and decades
before anybody every heard the

00:15:53.470 --> 00:15:58.570 position:56%
phrase world music or understood the
connection of vernacular cultures

00:15:58.570 --> 00:16:02.700
and traditional musical art forms.

00:16:02.700 --> 00:16:10.400
But Irwin saw the power in trying
to identify and make connections

00:16:10.400 --> 00:16:14.080
so that people would see their
own struggles and their own needs

00:16:14.080 --> 00:16:16.810
in the struggles of
other immigrant groups

00:16:16.810 --> 00:16:19.790
and other marginalized
portions to society.

00:16:19.790 --> 00:16:23.690
Now, for somebody who loves
folk music, what that ended

00:16:23.690 --> 00:16:27.920
up meaning was that you
could come into the magazine

00:16:27.920 --> 00:16:31.890
because you were really interested
in reading about Bill Monroe

00:16:31.890 --> 00:16:36.470
or finding out about
the collection --

00:16:36.470 --> 00:16:40.380
the collecting work that John Jacob
Miles did or something like that.

00:16:40.380 --> 00:16:44.770
But the way that it was presented
in Sing Out generally even

00:16:44.770 --> 00:16:53.130
if it was subtled up a lot
was presented with sort

00:16:53.130 --> 00:16:55.770 position:56%
of an undercurrent to it that let --

00:16:55.770 --> 00:17:00.680
that was shaped by the
political ideology that Irwin

00:17:00.680 --> 00:17:02.030
and the other [inaudible] people --

00:17:02.030 --> 00:17:07.840
now Pete Seger who was
one of the founders

00:17:07.840 --> 00:17:10.750
and honestly the reason
why Sing Out existed,

00:17:10.750 --> 00:17:14.190
the reason why Peoples Songs
existed is because Pete went

00:17:14.190 --> 00:17:16.450
to Harvard to become a journalist.

00:17:16.450 --> 00:17:18.430
That was always his dream.

00:17:18.430 --> 00:17:25.790
As I came to find out in a
difficult way as I was taking

00:17:25.790 --> 00:17:27.630
over the magazine, that this was --

00:17:27.630 --> 00:17:37.490 position:56%
even though Pete was everybody's
founding father of the folk revival,

00:17:37.490 --> 00:17:41.490
certainly my age and probably
a generation before me,

00:17:41.490 --> 00:17:45.650
Pete always saw himself as a
journalist that couldn't get a job

00:17:45.650 --> 00:17:48.390
in a newspaper so he ended
up being a folk singer

00:17:48.390 --> 00:17:52.400
and always wished he
could be an editor.

00:17:52.400 --> 00:17:57.790
I mean, jumping ahead for a second,
we -- when we were reforming --

00:17:57.790 --> 00:18:02.700
in 1981, Sing Out had
not published a magazine

00:18:02.700 --> 00:18:05.300
for about 1.5 year at
that point in time.

00:18:05.300 --> 00:18:10.110
And it was clear that the staff
based in the office in New York

00:18:10.110 --> 00:18:12.500
and decided that they were
going to pull the plug.

00:18:12.500 --> 00:18:16.990
So when I showed up at the
office to load up my car to take

00:18:16.990 --> 00:18:19.300
to the Hudson River
revival that year,

00:18:19.300 --> 00:18:23.220
they said don't sell any
subscriptions because we're done.

00:18:23.220 --> 00:18:25.030
We're out of here.

00:18:25.030 --> 00:18:27.570
We're -- so when I got to
the Hudson River revival

00:18:27.570 --> 00:18:32.100
which was also an event that was
created and founded by Pete --

00:18:32.100 --> 00:18:34.430
this time his organization
[inaudible].

00:18:34.430 --> 00:18:38.290
He too me aside.

00:18:38.290 --> 00:18:43.570
He was aware of what was going
on and we sort of sat along one

00:18:43.570 --> 00:18:45.400
of the heaps of garbage up there.

00:18:45.400 --> 00:18:49.420
And he said, "You know, Mark,
somehow, some way even if we've got

00:18:49.420 --> 00:18:51.880
to mimeograph this
magazine in somebody's face,

00:18:51.880 --> 00:18:54.020
we've got to keep Sing Out going."

00:18:54.020 --> 00:18:55.950
So we took a year.

00:18:55.950 --> 00:19:01.920
We published an interim newsletter,
which we sent out to the 1800

00:19:01.920 --> 00:19:05.950 position:56%
or so remaining subscribers
[inaudible] Sing Out's mailing list,

00:19:05.950 --> 00:19:07.250
fundraising.

00:19:07.250 --> 00:19:09.210
He did a series of
concerts raising money.

00:19:09.210 --> 00:19:10.510
We paid off the old debt,

00:19:10.510 --> 00:19:12.820
and we began putting
out the magazine again.

00:19:12.820 --> 00:19:15.480
And when we did the very first
issue, now my background --

00:19:15.480 --> 00:19:19.280
I mean, I went to Penn State
University, majored in English,

00:19:19.280 --> 00:19:22.600
minored in folklore, but I
had no experience doing this.

00:19:22.600 --> 00:19:24.990
I had been working as
a union electrician

00:19:24.990 --> 00:19:28.830
for about four years
before this occurred.

00:19:28.830 --> 00:19:31.900
So when I put out my first
issue of the magazine,

00:19:31.900 --> 00:19:34.980
it was rough shall we say.

00:19:34.980 --> 00:19:40.190
I knew nothing about -- it
was much room for improvement.

00:19:40.190 --> 00:19:43.780 position:56%
But Pete came to that first board
meeting,and we had assembled a board

00:19:43.780 --> 00:19:46.020
of directors that would
run a new nonprofit

00:19:46.020 --> 00:19:48.810
that we had created
to publish Sing Out.

00:19:48.810 --> 00:19:52.770
And they were all musicians, and
Pete came to that first meeting

00:19:52.770 --> 00:19:57.920
and like steam was coming out of
his ears because he hated the fact

00:19:57.920 --> 00:20:03.440
that I had put type on top of the
block print that he had procured

00:20:03.440 --> 00:20:07.290
to do the front cover of Sing
Out and didn't like how some

00:20:07.290 --> 00:20:09.420
of the things were edited
and how they were laid out.

00:20:09.420 --> 00:20:12.060
And he said, "Here's my idea.

00:20:12.060 --> 00:20:14.500
What we're going to do is
we're going to rent a truck,

00:20:14.500 --> 00:20:16.740
and we're going to load all
the file cabinets and a couple

00:20:16.740 --> 00:20:18.890
of desks in theback of the truck.

00:20:18.890 --> 00:20:21.020
And you're going to
drive from city to city.

00:20:21.020 --> 00:20:23.640
In each city, you're going to
roll off the back of the truck

00:20:23.640 --> 00:20:27.110
and people will walk by and will
say what are you doing in there?

00:20:27.110 --> 00:20:30.270
And then you'll say we're
doing a folk music magazine.

00:20:30.270 --> 00:20:33.320
Would you like to help?"

00:20:33.320 --> 00:20:34.620
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick:
That's Pete all right.

00:20:34.620 --> 00:20:37.220
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: And I said, Pete,

00:20:37.220 --> 00:20:41.600
if you want to do that,
you can do that.

00:20:41.600 --> 00:20:43.040
But I'm not doing that.

00:20:43.040 --> 00:20:48.680
And luckily there were other people
on the board at that time who stood

00:20:48.680 --> 00:20:54.140
up for me and Pete quit the
board for I think the first of --

00:20:54.140 --> 00:20:58.960
in my tenure a half dozen times
over the course of that --

00:20:58.960 --> 00:21:02.200
the 30 or so years
until Pete passed.

00:21:02.200 --> 00:21:03.500
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: I think
Pete's father would have done

00:21:03.500 --> 00:21:05.150
that if it had been him.

00:21:05.150 --> 00:21:07.910
Charlie would have done that,
driven around in a truck.

00:21:07.910 --> 00:21:09.210
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: Yeah, yeah.

00:21:09.210 --> 00:21:10.510
Absolutely.

00:21:10.510 --> 00:21:11.810
I have no doubt that
Pete would have done it

00:21:11.810 --> 00:21:15.570
if he didn't have those pesky
tour commitments and things.

00:21:15.570 --> 00:21:21.920
But getting back to the history of
things, so when Sing Out revived

00:21:21.920 --> 00:21:29.950
in 1950, this was sort of like the
beginning of the Hugh Act period

00:21:29.950 --> 00:21:34.990
of what was going on here, and
pretty much everybody affiliated

00:21:34.990 --> 00:21:39.920
with Peoples Artists ended up
getting either named or subpoenaed

00:21:39.920 --> 00:21:43.030
or questioned or blacklisted,

00:21:43.030 --> 00:21:48.460
and in one way it created a
comaraderie amongst people,

00:21:48.460 --> 00:21:57.260 position:56%
and the growth of people that were
involved in Peoples Artists and Sing

00:21:57.260 --> 00:22:01.560
Out in those days grew to
include people like Norman Lear

00:22:01.560 --> 00:22:10.920
and of course Paul Robson came back
briefly out of exile and was sort

00:22:10.920 --> 00:22:14.410
of worshipped amongst the
staff at Sing Out and stuff.

00:22:14.410 --> 00:22:20.660
But careful looking would see
that while the first seven'ish,

00:22:20.660 --> 00:22:22.040
almost eight years of Sing

00:22:22.040 --> 00:22:27.260 position:56%
Out included a Peoples Artist
publication underneath the mast head

00:22:27.260 --> 00:22:33.420
and as theownership, it disappeared
by the end of the 1950's and sort

00:22:33.420 --> 00:22:38.820
of quietly Peoples Artists
ceased to exist and Irwin Silber

00:22:38.820 --> 00:22:45.490
who was not a musician himself but
certainly not a performing musician

00:22:45.490 --> 00:22:51.980
but a pretty able organizer

00:22:51.980 --> 00:22:58.690
and entrepreneur took ownership
and took over Sing Out.

00:22:58.690 --> 00:23:04.960
He also had partial involvement or
[inaudible] had partial involvement

00:23:04.960 --> 00:23:09.360
in ownership in Sing Out during
those days, though that sort of --

00:23:09.360 --> 00:23:11.440
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: [Inaudible]
ran [inaudible]'s recordings,

00:23:11.440 --> 00:23:18.150
which are now -- it was taken over
by the Smithsonian in the late 70's

00:23:18.150 --> 00:23:19.450
and now Smithsonian [inaudible].

00:23:19.450 --> 00:23:24.060
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: And then as
the 50's came to a close,

00:23:24.060 --> 00:23:29.130
Irwin also started a publishing
company called Oak Publications,

00:23:29.130 --> 00:23:34.610
which was responsible
for many of most

00:23:34.610 --> 00:23:40.000
of the real important
collections and instruction books

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:43.010
and song books and stuff.

00:23:43.010 --> 00:23:47.120
So he -- Sing Out would
share offices with --

00:23:47.120 --> 00:23:53.670
on and off from the mid 50's
up until the late 1960's

00:23:53.670 --> 00:23:56.310
with some combination of
[inaudible] Publications, whatever.

00:23:56.310 --> 00:24:05.660 position:56%
In 1965, Irwin who had already begun
doing a lot more overt political

00:24:05.660 --> 00:24:09.750
writing had decided that
the ship had kind of sailed

00:24:09.750 --> 00:24:16.340
from folk music being a way to
make his political statement

00:24:16.340 --> 00:24:18.910
and kind of receded from it.

00:24:18.910 --> 00:24:24.930
He sold Oak Publications to music
sales and ended up selling Sing

00:24:24.930 --> 00:24:30.960
Out separately to a cooperative
of people including Manny Solomon

00:24:30.960 --> 00:24:37.770
of Vanguard, Mo, Howard
Leventhal, Pete, and they formed

00:24:37.770 --> 00:24:42.070
yet another corporation that
was putting out a magazine

00:24:42.070 --> 00:24:47.030
that was now starting off
saddled with about a $20,000 debt

00:24:47.030 --> 00:24:50.610 position:56%
because all of these people had put
money in the pot, which bought Irwin

00:24:50.610 --> 00:24:56.230
out and Irwin went off
to work for The Guardian.

00:24:56.230 --> 00:25:00.910
And [inaudible] became the
editor for about 18 months

00:25:00.910 --> 00:25:04.410
or so during that period of time.

00:25:04.410 --> 00:25:08.360
And Sing Out really
radically made a shift

00:25:08.360 --> 00:25:13.200
because Happy's orientation
was not Irwin's.

00:25:13.200 --> 00:25:17.090
Happy's orientation was much more
-- because that was really --

00:25:17.090 --> 00:25:21.790
it was right after Happy's tenure
when I discovered the magazine.

00:25:21.790 --> 00:25:30.430
So he was much more into being
excited by the connection

00:25:30.430 --> 00:25:35.170
of traditions into contemporary
and sort of the evolution

00:25:35.170 --> 00:25:37.390
of the folk process
and that kind of stuff

00:25:37.390 --> 00:25:44.130 position:56%
that had always been the dressing of
what Sing Out was, but the politics

00:25:44.130 --> 00:25:48.830
of it sort of took a
different role in the --

00:25:48.830 --> 00:25:53.480
in what the magazine was doing.

00:25:53.480 --> 00:25:58.580
So Happy tried to keep things
going for a couple of years

00:25:58.580 --> 00:26:05.070
and then what we had was a
series of semi catastrophies

00:26:05.070 --> 00:26:11.230 position:56%
and financial difficulties mostly
having to do with the financial debt

00:26:11.230 --> 00:26:16.650
that they had during this point
in time while they were putting

00:26:16.650 --> 00:26:26.490
out sort of a glorified fanzine
in an era that was not a DIY era.

00:26:26.490 --> 00:26:31.190
So while Sing Out during
its most prominent era --

00:26:31.190 --> 00:26:36.430
period during those early
1960's years leading

00:26:36.430 --> 00:26:40.010
up to Irwin being disenchanted
had its --

00:26:40.010 --> 00:26:43.580
its subscription base
had risen to I think --

00:26:43.580 --> 00:26:46.620
it's difficult to tell
because everybody lies

00:26:46.620 --> 00:26:52.360
on their second class distribution
that they post in the magazine

00:26:52.360 --> 00:26:54.950
but it seemed to be
somewhere between about 12,000

00:26:54.950 --> 00:26:59.300
and 15,000 copies were being
printed at its highest moment

00:26:59.300 --> 00:27:02.930
up to that point in time.

00:27:02.930 --> 00:27:07.530
But by the time the early
70's had rolled around,

00:27:07.530 --> 00:27:11.930
it had shrunk back again to down
to just a couple of thousand,

00:27:11.930 --> 00:27:16.920
and it was difficult to figure
out how to continue doing it.

00:27:16.920 --> 00:27:19.060
The format of the magazine changed.

00:27:19.060 --> 00:27:22.020
They tried in the mid 1970's.

00:27:22.020 --> 00:27:26.100
They issued a flexi disk in
every other issue of the magazine

00:27:26.100 --> 00:27:28.560
that included just the
first verse and chorus

00:27:28.560 --> 00:27:30.590
of the songs that were
being printed.

00:27:30.590 --> 00:27:35.330
But there was a lot of editorial
turnover during that period of time

00:27:35.330 --> 00:27:37.680
so would go for like
a couple of issues

00:27:37.680 --> 00:27:39.750
where it would be very
much connected,

00:27:39.750 --> 00:27:43.030
and there'd be thematic issues
were put out for instance

00:27:43.030 --> 00:27:45.530
in the bicentennial year
that were each talking

00:27:45.530 --> 00:27:47.530 position:56%
about different immigrant traditions

00:27:47.530 --> 00:27:51.090
or Native American cultures
and stuff like that.

00:27:51.090 --> 00:27:52.940
And then there were
other periods of times

00:27:52.940 --> 00:28:00.420
where it took a very pointed dive
toward the uber political and what

00:28:00.420 --> 00:28:04.290
that ended up doing was the
audience that was there,

00:28:04.290 --> 00:28:06.170
the people who were showing

00:28:06.170 --> 00:28:10.050
up for the politics would go why
are you covering this other stuff?

00:28:10.050 --> 00:28:11.350
And the people that were showing

00:28:11.350 --> 00:28:17.590
up for traditional music were
saying what do you mean Puerto

00:28:17.590 --> 00:28:20.560
Rican independence?

00:28:20.560 --> 00:28:27.880
So they continued to have
problems which led up to the end

00:28:27.880 --> 00:28:33.730
of the 1970's -- 1980
was the final issue

00:28:33.730 --> 00:28:38.590
that the New York team
put out as a magazine.

00:28:38.590 --> 00:28:39.890
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: It's
interesting because it kind

00:28:39.890 --> 00:28:43.100
of shows two different
ways in which politics

00:28:43.100 --> 00:28:45.850
and music interact in a magazine.

00:28:45.850 --> 00:28:48.580
So you're talking about
people wanting

00:28:48.580 --> 00:28:52.910
to cover overtly political things
like Puerto Rican independence,

00:28:52.910 --> 00:28:55.920
but at the same time that shift

00:28:55.920 --> 00:29:01.740
in the bicentennial [inaudible]
immigrant cultures was a political

00:29:01.740 --> 00:29:04.140
thing in the United
States at that time,

00:29:04.140 --> 00:29:06.130
though not perceived as political.

00:29:06.130 --> 00:29:08.080
For the most part,
perceived as cultural.

00:29:08.080 --> 00:29:11.070
So Sing Out was covering
both of those things,

00:29:11.070 --> 00:29:12.910
and you're saying it was
maybe a little uncomfortable

00:29:12.910 --> 00:29:15.630
for the audience?

00:29:15.630 --> 00:29:16.930
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: Yeah.

00:29:16.930 --> 00:29:22.030
I mean, look, when we went
through that period of time in 1982

00:29:22.030 --> 00:29:24.930
when Pete and I were editing that
newsletter and we were asking

00:29:24.930 --> 00:29:28.930
for input about what do you want
Sing Out to be going forward kind

00:29:28.930 --> 00:29:34.850
of discussion, ultimately what
we found out was is that the base

00:29:34.850 --> 00:29:37.580
of people that we had that
were still reading the magazine

00:29:37.580 --> 00:29:40.560
at that time were in -- were --

00:29:40.560 --> 00:29:46.090
it was sort of like five
Jews at a dinner party.

00:29:46.090 --> 00:29:47.820
There were 12 opinions.

00:29:47.820 --> 00:29:49.120
And --

00:29:49.120 --> 00:29:50.930 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick: No, you're wrong.

00:29:50.930 --> 00:29:59.450
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: So ultimately
we decided two main things.

00:29:59.450 --> 00:30:04.180
I mean, we as this
forming board came together

00:30:04.180 --> 00:30:05.910
to create the nonprofit
that would go

00:30:05.910 --> 00:30:08.790
on to publish Sing Out since then.

00:30:08.790 --> 00:30:13.050
Was first and foremost
was we wanted Sing

00:30:13.050 --> 00:30:17.300
Out to be a folk music
magazine connecting traditional

00:30:17.300 --> 00:30:22.200
and contemporary folk music
and looking at how it interacts

00:30:22.200 --> 00:30:27.830
with our every day lives and helped
people make that music a part

00:30:27.830 --> 00:30:31.060
of how they did the
things that they did.

00:30:31.060 --> 00:30:34.640
But music was going to be
the driving force behind it.

00:30:34.640 --> 00:30:42.940
We would look to the music
first and follow the politics

00:30:42.940 --> 00:30:46.100 position:56%
that are always coupled and inherent

00:30:46.100 --> 00:30:53.910
in what true community vernacular
orally transmitted music is

00:30:53.910 --> 00:30:59.430
because by its very nature,
if you're regionally trying

00:30:59.430 --> 00:31:06.070
to celebrate your culture, you
are making a political statement

00:31:06.070 --> 00:31:13.750
in a day and age that doesn't
honor that and doesn't celebrate

00:31:13.750 --> 00:31:21.060
that in that kind of a way.

00:31:21.060 --> 00:31:28.840
But the second part of it is, to be
fair, is we weren't sort of trying

00:31:28.840 --> 00:31:31.660
to be fair or balanced
about our politics either.

00:31:31.660 --> 00:31:37.280
We have a history of coming out
of leftist political movements.

00:31:37.280 --> 00:31:39.870
And that's where we stayed.

00:31:39.870 --> 00:31:47.940
So -- but by -- I think by
shifting that focus by deciding

00:31:47.940 --> 00:31:52.650
that the magazine was going to
always try to be a smorgasbord

00:31:52.650 --> 00:31:57.180
to a certain extent and
to include some politics,

00:31:57.180 --> 00:32:00.540 position:56%
some stuff about just the community,
some stuff about the history

00:32:00.540 --> 00:32:04.950
of music, some stuff about how to
play the music, in each issue --

00:32:04.950 --> 00:32:09.150
and try to do that -- we were
able to retain that membership

00:32:09.150 --> 00:32:13.710
and build our subscriber
base again by the late 80's,

00:32:13.710 --> 00:32:18.770
early 90's back up to about 15,000.

00:32:18.770 --> 00:32:25.410
Now, of course, that was the 1990's
and the beginnings of the internet.

00:32:25.410 --> 00:32:27.780
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: In the meantime,

00:32:27.780 --> 00:32:30.360
the office had moved
to Pennsylvania, right?

00:32:30.360 --> 00:32:31.660
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: Right.

00:32:31.660 --> 00:32:39.550
After the 1981 Hudson River
revival, some friends of mine

00:32:39.550 --> 00:32:43.060
and I rented a U-Haul
truck, drove up to New York,

00:32:43.060 --> 00:32:46.030
parked across the street
from 505 Eighth Avenue

00:32:46.030 --> 00:32:52.660 position:56%
where we were subletting -- Sing Out
was subletting 2.5 rooms from WBAL,

00:32:52.660 --> 00:32:56.810
the Pacifica radio station in New
York, and we loaded up the truck

00:32:56.810 --> 00:33:00.480
like to the ceiling with
all the magazines, books,

00:33:00.480 --> 00:33:02.190
recordings, file cabinets.

00:33:02.190 --> 00:33:05.920
And then I went out, got in the
truck and tried to pull out,

00:33:05.920 --> 00:33:09.980
but the entire back of the
truck was on the wheels.

00:33:09.980 --> 00:33:15.590
So we went and rented another
truck and emptied out the one

00:33:15.590 --> 00:33:18.660
into the other one, and
we moved to Pennsylvania.

00:33:18.660 --> 00:33:21.430
At that point in time, we really
didn't know what was going on.

00:33:21.430 --> 00:33:24.750
We just knew we couldn't
continue to pay rent to WBAI

00:33:24.750 --> 00:33:28.360
because we were months
in arrears at that point.

00:33:28.360 --> 00:33:34.810
We owed the printer about
$12,000 which in 1982 money was --

00:33:34.810 --> 00:33:36.110
&gt;&gt; Stephen Winick:
Pretty substantial, yeah.

00:33:36.110 --> 00:33:37.520
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: Pretty substantial.

00:33:37.520 --> 00:33:39.300
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: And
so you went down to --

00:33:39.300 --> 00:33:41.740
where you're originally
from -- to Easton?

00:33:41.740 --> 00:33:46.030
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: I grew up in the
Lehigh Valley so we went to Easton,

00:33:46.030 --> 00:33:50.700 position:56%
unloaded the truck into the basement
of my friend's bicycle shop,

00:33:50.700 --> 00:33:54.930
you know Genesis Bicycles
still there if you want to --

00:33:54.930 --> 00:33:59.570
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Give
them business, yes.

00:33:59.570 --> 00:34:05.510 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: And then like a little
over a year after that in December

00:34:05.510 --> 00:34:11.770
of 1982, we published a final
issue of the newsletter and said

00:34:11.770 --> 00:34:15.910 position:56%
that we would be -- in the spring we
would be putting out the first issue

00:34:15.910 --> 00:34:20.590
of a new revitalized Sing Out
published by Sing Out Corporation,

00:34:20.590 --> 00:34:28.040
this new nonprofit that we
had formed and then we set

00:34:28.040 --> 00:34:32.280
up an office upstairs from a
friend of mine's woodworking shop

00:34:32.280 --> 00:34:35.980
and got ready and put
that first issue out.

00:34:35.980 --> 00:34:39.840
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: And then you
moved again many years later

00:34:39.840 --> 00:34:42.570
into your building
in Bethlehem, right?

00:34:42.570 --> 00:34:43.870
&gt;&gt; Mark Moss: Yeah.

00:34:43.870 --> 00:34:45.170
We've moved twice.

00:34:45.170 --> 00:34:50.160
We moved to another place in
Bethlehem about five years later

